04981nam a22006615i 9780822385097DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223850977 a10.1515/97808223850972doi  a(DE-B1597)553557  a(OCoLC)1226679571  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPR9205.05b.J64 2003 7aLIT0041002bisacsh04a810.9/89607292211 aJohn, Catherine A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClear Word and Third Sight :bFolk Groundings and Diasporic Consciousness in African Caribbean Writing /cCatherine A. John; ed. by Donald E. Pease. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (254 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists : 1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Alternate Consciousness in the Diaspora -- t1 Paris in 1956: Negritude and Cultural Discourse -- t2 Colonial Legacies, Gender Identity, and Black Female Writing in the Diaspora -- t3 Negritude and Negativity: Alienation and ‘‘Voice’’ in Eastern Caribbean Literature -- t4 Diaspora Philosophy, French Caribbean Literature, and Simone Schwarz-Bart’s Pluie et vent sur Télumée Miracle -- t5 The Spoken Word and Spirit Consciousness: Audre Lorde and Paule Marshall’s Diasporic Voice -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClear Word and Third Sight examines the strands of a collective African diasporic consciousness represented in the work of a number of Black Caribbean writers. Catherine A. John shows how a shared consciousness, or “third sight,” is rooted in both pre- and postcolonial cultural practices and disseminated through a rich oral tradition. This consciousness has served diasporic communities by creating an alternate philosophical “worldsense” linking those of African descent across space and time.Contesting popular discourses about what constitutes culture and maintaining that neglected strains in negritude discourse provide a crucial philosophical perspective on the connections between folk practices, cultural memory, and collective consciousness, John examines the diasporic principles in the work of the negritude writers Léon Damas, Aimé Césaire, and Léopold Senghor. She traces the manifestations and reworkings of their ideas in Afro-Caribbean writing from the eastern and French Caribbean, as well as the Caribbean diaspora in the United States. The authors she discusses include Jamaica Kincaid, Earl Lovelace, Simone Schwarz-Bart, Audre Lorde, Paule Marshall, and Edouard Glissant, among others. John argues that by incorporating what she calls folk groundings—such as poems, folktales, proverbs, and songs—into their work, Afro-Caribbean writers invoke a psychospiritual consciousness which combines old and new strategies for addressing the ongoing postcolonial struggle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican literaturexAppreciationzCaribbean Area. 0aBlack people in literature. 0aBlacks in literature. 0aCaribbean literature (English)xAfrican influences. 0aCaribbean literature (English)xBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCaribbean literature (French)xAfrican influences. 0aCaribbean literature (French)xBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFolklore in literature. 0aFolklorezCaribbean Area. 0aLiterature and folklorezCaribbean Area. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aPease, Donald E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385097zCo-access DOI >> click Walt